Kevin C 25-Oct-19 08:50 PM
for those who asked about dp today: 1. find out what the state is. this is the data that you need to keep track of. in golf, that data is distance. in mouse journey, it is the numbers of possible paths to get to each cage. you'll also need to store this data. in golf, since distance is 1D, you can store it in an array. consider how you would store 2D data from mouse journey. 2. identify the start and end states. this is what state your dp program will start at and what part of the states you are looking for. in golf, that is simply the 0th index of the distance array and the (n-1)th index of the distance array, in which it starts at a state of 0 distance and ends at a state of n distance. in mouse journey, the problem statement tells you to go from position (1, 1) to position (R, C). what state would position (1, 1) be at considering that the state is the number of possible paths to get to that position? 3. find a transition for the program to run. you should create a dp structure separate to the one you are using to store the inputted data. in golf, that structure is a 1D array as the distance is 1D. next, think about how to get from the start state to the end state. in golf, it is to try out all the clubs. in mouse journey, pay attention to the restrictions on how the mouse can move according to the problem statement (obviously the mouse cannot just move freely otherwise it would be able to move in an infinite amount of looping paths). how would you account for cats? (think about referring to the inputted data while modifying the dp structure). that is all i can think of in terms of hints on how to solve mouse journey. if you have other questions just ask me here. this channel could be like an unofficial forum for the club or something. @Zack C @Samuel G @Luca O(edited)

@Zack C distance should not be an integer. instead of using a 'visited' boolean array to store visited nodes, think about how you can store the distances of all the nodes instead and use that (think about the logic used when doing bfs, the same things apply for dfs, you need to store each distance rather than having a temporary variable. what data structure can hold many variables?). dont use the 'locker' boolean. there is an easier way to do it. think about where the starting position should be. is there a starting position that lets you get both distances quickly? dont use sys.exit(). recursive functions always end in a base (meaning you should return the function or let it reach the end rather than forcing it to exit) @Samuel G you are doing bfs but i'll allow it. you are currently using two vectors: v and d. from what i understand one holds the distances and the other holds if it has been visited after the locker or not. try instead to use two distance arrays with no visited array. the traversal is in two parts so have two arrays for each one. (optimization: an even better way is to only have one distance array. note my suggestion to zack. what starting point is the optimal starting point to get the two values with one dfs/bfs call?) for c++, you can do 2 dfs, time complexity O(2n^2) for java/python you will need the optimization, time complexity O(n^2)(edited)
